sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/common/utils.message:
Yeah, it's kind of unfortunate that this function is being called in multiple places in the code on plain IP address/domain (_validate_SAN_list), url (_validate_oidc_issuer_url), and docker registry path (_validate_docker_registry_address).  Same thing goes for some of the ansible-playbook validations (registry path or plain ip/domain).  For example to use this function with a URL (as in _validate_oidc_issuer_url), they are first stripping off the http://

It makes the whole thing a bit messy IMO.  Especially since now the port is being validated as well, which doesn't really match with the name of the function.

I think a somewhat cleaner solution would probably be to have this function simply do what the name implies:

    if is_valid_ip(data):
        return True
    elif is_valid_domain(data):
        return True

For an URL, I believe the existing is_url() validates both the IPv4/IPv6 address and port.

For a registry path, something like urlparse could be used. The only kind of gotcha there is that for a registry path (not having a preceeding http) one needs to prepend the string with // for urlparse to work properly.  In addition, depending on the version of urlparse, the port validation will either throw a ValueError, or the port field will be None.  Something roughly like this:

=====================

def is_valid_domain_or_ip(host):
    if host and '[' in host:
        try:
            bkt_idx = host.index(']')
            host = host[1:bkt_idx]
        except Exception:
            return False
    if is_valid_ip(host):
        return True
    elif is_valid_domain(host):
        return True
    return False

def is_valid_port(port):
   if not port or port not in range(1, 65535):
       return False
   return True

def is_valid_url_or_registry_path(url_str):
    if not url_str:
        return False

    # url: this will validate the address and port (if present)
    if is_url(url_str):
        return True

    # registry path, need to append at least '//' for urlparse
    if not url_str.startswith('http'):
        url_str = '//' + url_str
    try:
        parsed_url=urlparse(url_str, 'http')
    except ValueError:
        return False

    port = parsed_url.port

    # older versions of urlparse may set 'port' to None if it is invalid.
    # detect this by comparing the length of the hostname with the netloc
    if (port is None and (len(parsed_url.hostname) != len(parsed_url.netloc.strip("[]")))):
        port = parsed_url.netloc.rsplit(':', 1)
        if len(port) != 2:
            return False
        port = port[1]
    if port and not is_valid_port(port):
        return False

    return is_valid_domain_or_ip(parsed_url.hostname)

===================

Doing it this way would imply calling out to the appropriate function as necessary, and would of course require rigorous testing each of those scenarios.  I suppose if necessary we could leave that as a further enhancement.

